  "text": "For the LES, t j i is interpreted as a subgrid-scale stress tensor, and the viscosity and thermal conductivity are interpreted as subgrid-scale eddy coeficients that must be modeled. Since no well accepted approach currently exists for LES when large subgrid-scale gradients of buoyancy and temperature may be present, we adopt a conventional method that has been shown to be successful for buoyancy-dominated boundary layers (e.g. Deardorff 1973; [CITATION_1] and acknowledge at this point that this approach may not be entirely appropriate. In this scheme, the eddy viscosity depends on the subgrid-scale turbulent kinetic energy, e, as follows p = p~k e 1 / 2~, (8) where Ck is a constant and A is the grid spacing. The eddy conductivity is then related to the eddy viscosity via a turbulent Prandtl number of the form given by equation (7), which is assumed to be equal to 1/3 herein. To close the model, Wildland fires rarely exhibit such simple configurations, at ax/ however, and the maximum heat release is seldom located in gk 86 pc,e3j2 the centre of the fire area. Typically, fires possess an asym------cp8 3. z a (9) metric ring-like structure that is elliptical (with major axis in the streamwise direction), most intense at its forwards end where the last term on the right-hand side represents the dis-(the head), less intense on the sides (the flanks), and weakest sipation of subgrid-scale turbulent kinetic energy. Following at its rear end (the back). Consequently, in this paper we also Moeng and Wyngaard ( 1 988), values for the constants in consider heat sources with shapes that are representative of equation (8) and equation (9) are chosen to be Ck = 0.1 and this typical structure; specifically, the following functional C, = 0.93. It is important to note, however, that these numform for the heat source is adopted: bers are empirically defined based on Kolmogorov inertialsubrange theory, and a variety of different values both for Q(x.y, z, t) = Qo tanh(t/to)